      <div xml:id="NA199-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu vaṉpoṟai (ER, ET, EV: vaṉpuṟai) etiraḻintatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is being desolate in the face of consolation.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA199">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            ōṅkumaṇa luṭutta neṭumāp peṇṇai</l>
<l>            vīṅkumaṭaṟ kuṭampaip paital veṇkuruku</l>
<l>            naḷḷeṉ yāmat tuyavutō ṟuruki</l>
<l>            yaḷḷa laṉṉave ṉuḷḷamō ṭuḷḷuṭain</l>
<l>            tuḷḷeṉ vāḻi tōḻi vaḷainīrk </l>
<l>            kaṭuñcuṟā veṟinta koṭuntimiṟ paratavar</l>
<l>            vāṅkuvicait tūṇṭi lūṅkūṅ kāki</l>
<l>            vaḷiporak kaṟṟai tāay naḷicuṭar</l>
<l>            nīṉiṟa vicumpiṉ mīṉoṭu puraiyap</l>
<l>            paipaya vimaikkun tuṟaivaṉ </l>
<l>            meytōy muyakkaṅ kāṇā vūṅkē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>I won't remember<note place="foot">T.V.G. reads here, with EN and ET: <term xml:lang="ta">uḷaṉē vāḻi tōḻi</term> "I [still] exist, oh friend." Actually, both variants do not go well with the usual impact of the <term xml:lang="ta">ūṅku</term> constructions which is that of temporal anteriority. So here we have to understand something like "until" for the whole to make sense.</note>, oh friend,</l>
<l rend="indent2">        broken inside, with my mind like mire,</l>
<l rend="indent2">        melting with every [sound of] suffering at deepest midnight</l>
<l rend="indent">        from the distressed white egret<note place="foot">T.V.G. in this place wants to take the <term xml:lang="ta">veṇ kuruku</term> for an <term xml:lang="ta">Aṉṟil</term>.</note> in [its] nest in the swelling</l>
<l rend="indent4">             palmyra stems,</l>
<l rend="indent3">        on the long big palmyra tree encircled by high sand,</l>
<l>    – before I see the embrace touch [my] body</l>
<l rend="indent2">        of the man from the ghat, where the huge lamps,</l>
<l rend="indent">        spreading bundles of light when the wind hits them,</l>
<l rend="indent">        here [and] there on the fish-hooks speedily pulled by the fishermen</l>
<l rend="indent3">        in [their] bent boats who had thrown up fierce sharks</l>
<l rend="indent4">            in the curved waters,</l>
<l rend="indent2">        are gently twinkling</l>
<l rend="indent3">        similar to<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">mīṉoṭu puraiya</term>: here we find the rather strange incident of a word of comparison construed with an instrumental instead of the fairly usual accusative (if marked at all). T.V.G. knows it to occur rarely</note> the stars in the blue-coloured sky.</l>
        </lg>
